title: Jewish prisoners load textiles onto a truck from a Madritch factory warehouse.  The Madritch factory utilized concentration camp labor in Plaszow to produce uniforms for the German army.
View of a destroyed building in Kovno which housed the G. Gutman Judaica store.
Undertakers from the funeral home of M.B. Pinkiert unload bodies from a cart into a mass grave in the Warsaw ghetto cemetery.

German civilians carry corpses on stretchers to be buried in mass graves.  The victims are concentration camp prisoners who were killed by the SS in a barn, shown in the background, just outside Gardelegen.
The Yiddish words, "Jews Revenge!" scrawled in blood on the apartment floor of a Jew murdered in the Slobodka pogrom.  [oversized photo]
Survivors of the Dachau concentration camp demonstrate the operation of the crematorium by preparing a corpse to be placed into one of the ovens.
Hitler poses holding the "blood flag" from the Beer Hall Putsch of 1923 at the fourth Nazi Party Congress.
Former SS Lt. Heinz Tomhardt is sentenced to death by hanging by an American Military Tribunal for his part in the Malmedy massacre.

Former SS-Hauptsturmfuehrer Doctor Willi Jobst, a defendant at the trial of 61 former camp personnel and prisoners from Mauthausen, stands in his place in the defendants' dock.  Dr. Jobst was camp physician of the Ebensee concentration camp.
Portrait of Jozef and Genia Berkowicz with their daughter Rita in Warsaw.
Theresienstadt ghetto currency.
The judges of Military Tribunal VI during the I.G. Farben Trial.  From left to right are James Morris, Curtis G. Shake, Paul M. Hebert, and Clarence F. Merrell.
Hungarian-Jewish conscripts in the Hungarian Labor Service prepare for their journey back to Ungvar, Hungary.
Page from the anti-semitic German children's book, "Trau Keinem Fuchs..."  (Trust No Fox in the Green Meadow and No Jew on his Oath)
Portrait of the donor's uncle, Moshe Kaplan, wearing an embroidered blouse (a Jewish folkdancing costume).
Portrait of Laici Rosenthal, one of the seven Kaufering babies born to the women of the Schwanger [pregnancy] Kommando in the Kaufering concentration camp in the winter of 1945.
Two Jewish refugees ride in a pedicab.
Group portrait of the Rosner and Krausz families at the wedding of Imre Rosner and Klara Krausz in Budapest.
Hirsch Glicenstein poses with his young nephew, Leo Grinberg, in front of a brick house in Kalisz.
Passport issued to Eva Rosenbaum a few days before she left on a Kindertransport to England.
A group of Jewish youth pose outside the Rothschild's Chateau Ferriere, where they are attending a summer camp sponsored by OSE.
Portrait of Solomon Ergas, son of Yosef Ergas.  He was a student.  He lived at Dalmatinska 78 in Bitola.
Eli Kalm (left) and William Bernstein, crew members of the President Warfield/Exodus 1947, converse on the deck of the ship before its departure for Europe.
A group of Jewish DPs crowd around Nahum Goldmann during an official visit to the Zeilsheim displaced persons camp.
Group portrait of members of the 2nd Polish Corps (Anders Army) band while they were stationed in Palestine.
Group portrait of some of the younger children at the Mariaburg DP children's home near Antwerp.
Group portrait of members of the I.L. Peretz drama club in Czortkow.
Visitors pose with glasses of mineral water in front of a hotel at the Bad Hall resort.

Newspaper clipping featuring a photograph of the joint orchestras of the Juedischer Kulturbund [Jewish Cultural Association] and the Kuenstlerhilfe der Juedischen Gemeinde zu Berlin [Artists Aid of the Jewish Community of Berlin] under the direction of Berthold Sander.
Group portrait of SS officers in front of a barrack in the Hinzert concentration camp.
Jewish leaders attend a meeting of the World Jewish Congress in Montreux, Switzerland.
Receipt for 30 francs sent to Chaim Cheichanow from the Auxilliary Mutual Bank for Family Allocation.
Portrait of two women and a young child in the Tarnow ghetto.
Herman Goering is escorted by an American serviceman following his capture.
Studio portrait of an unidentified woman holding a young infant, relatives of Regina Goldberg.
Family portrait of the Lieberman family in Pabianice.
Grou portrait of faculty and students at the technical university in Verviers, Belgium.

Unauthorized Salvadoran citizenship certificated issued to Leo van Emden (b. June 10, 1915 in Rotterdam), his wife Josette van Emden (b. July 16, 1916 in Lausanne) and their daughter Jacqueline (b. July 19, 1940) by George Mandel-Mantello, First Secretary of the Salvadoran Consulate in Switzerland and sent to their residence in Rotterdam.
Polish citizens walk down a street of Warsaw.
Franz Lieberman writes at a table with his mother looking on.
Young men and women wearing white shirts and ties march in a Nazi parade in Frankfurt.
Illustrated page from the diary of Egon Weiss, showing the sinking of the Patria, which he compiled during and immediately after his detention in the camp.
Harry Markowicz poses for a portrait shortly after liberation.
Two Jewish men shovel snow in the Krosno ghetto.
A young German soldier tries on his gas mask during basic training.
Edith Heller and her daughter Ruth pose outside their Sukkah.  They built the Sukkah on the roof of their apartment in a retirement home in celebration of Sukkot.
Pedestrians gather around a poster advertising joint speeches to be held by Hitler and Mussolini in Berlin.
Etching on the front page of the Nazi publication, Der Stuermer, depicting a ritual murder.
Chief Rabbi of Palestine, Isaac Herzog, pays an official visit to the Zeilsheim displaced persons' camp.
Jewish DPs commemorate the death march from Dachau to Tyrol while they hold a protest against British immigration policy to Palestine at the Mittenwald displaced persons camp.
A group of young Jewish DPs pose on a street in the Lampertheim displaced persons camp.
Letter written by Varian Fry to the American consul at the U.S. embassy in Vichy seeking his help in obtaining an exit visa for Walter Meyerhof.
Two Jewish men at forced labor clearing rubble in Konskowola.
A section of the Maginot Line, after the defeat of France by the German army.

Notice to MS St. Louis passengers from the passenger committee and the ship's crew, typewritten on Hamburg-Amerika Line letterhead, informing passengers that landing in Havana remains a possibility, and asking them to be hopeful and ready to respond to an official confirmation of permission to land.
Prisoners at forced labor in the Wiener Graben quarry at the Mauthausen concentration camp.
A Nazi rally in front of the "Voelkerschlachtsdenkmal" the monument commemorating the defeat of Napoleon in 1813.
Survivors sit on the floor in the infirmary barracks for Jewish prisoners in the Ebensee concentration camp.
Corpses piled in a wooded area near Bergen-Belsen.
Jewish women and children from Subcarpathian Rus who have been selected for death at Auschwitz-Birkenau, walk toward the gas chambers.
Jewish women and children from Subcarpathian Rus who have been selected for death at Auschwitz-Birkenau, walk toward the gas chambers.
Troops with the American 82nd Airborne Division examine corpses found in the latrine of the Woebbelin concentration camp.
Passengers lounge on the deck of the refugee ship MS St. Louis.
A cantor sings at a public ceremony sponsored by the Central Committee of Liberated Jews in the U.S. Zone of Germany.
A group of Jews return to the ghetto after forced labor on the outside. Here, they line-up to be searched. Jewish police stand among them.
Two women work on a large agricultural plot in the Kovno ghetto.

The corpse of a Jewish prisoner who was gassed at Natzweiler-Struthof and whose body was kept in a vat of alcohol at the Strasbourg University Anatomical Institute for over a year until it was discovered by Allied forces.
The sanctuary of a synagogue in Hanau, Germany.
A young Jewish boy studies his Hebrew reading book on the steps of his house in the old Jewish quarter of Rome.
The personal belongings of Jews killed at Babi Yar.
Women in the barracks of the newly liberated Auschwitz concentration camp.
Jews from Subcarpathian Rus who have been selected for forced labor at Auschwitz-Birkenau, wait to be taken to another section of the camp.
Corpses lined up on the west side of the barn with a visible hole supposedly made by a Panzerfaust.  In the background German civilians remove corpses from the barn.
The deportation of Jews from Westerbork.  Members of the Ordedienst (Jewish police) are visible in the foreground.
A group of German-Jewish refugee women and children aboard a Greek vessel [the Aghia Dezioni] on their way to Palestine.
The Olympic stadium in Berlin, site of the 11th Olympic Games.
David Ben-Gurion, Chairman of the Jewish Agency Executive, on an official visit to the Zeilsheim displaced persons camp.
An aerial view of the Mauthausen area. [Oversized Photo]
The bodies of two Czech prisoners shot in the Wiener Graben quarry at Mauthausen.
The Morgenstern family poses with their rescuer, Walentyna Zak, while living in hiding.
Portrait of Karl Brandt as a defendant in the Medical Case Trial at Nuremberg.
Members of the Wachenheimer family pose in front of their dry goods store.
Portrait of the Bocahut family at a wedding celebration (sitting to the groom's right).
Corporal Jack R. Nowitz (center), a lawyer on the staff of the Judge Advocate General, 3rd U.S. Army, checks books listing exterminations at Gusen.
Portrait of a German Jewish girl holding a Schultüte [school cone] full of candy on her first day of school in Leipzig.
Defendant Fritz Sauckel, the former Plenipotentiary General for Labor, in his prison cell at the International Military Tribunal trial of war criminals at Nuremberg.
Jews who are being forced to relocate to the Krakow ghetto move their belongings in carts and horse-drawn wagons across the bridge over the Vistula River.
Portrait of a young Jewish woman in Sosnowiec, Poland.
A Jewish man and woman from Sejny sit outside a wooden house.
The courtroom during the Krupp Trial.
The front of a post card sent from Iva Ledec, a German Jewish prisoner in Theresienstadt, to Juliana Behounek.
William Bernstein, aged 23, a member of the crew of the President Warfield/Exodus 1947, poses on the deck of the ship before its departure for Europe.

Corpses that were removed from the central barracks (Boelke Kaserne) lie in rows, while in the background an American soldier orders assembled German civilians from the nearby town of Nordhausen to begin transporting the bodies to a nearby mass grave for burial.
The barbed-wire fence and moat that surrounded the Dachau concentration camp.
A Jewish couple wearing armbands stands near the Hungarian-Jewish Labor Camp where Company 108/57 was housed.
Fritz and Babette Spanier stand at the rail of the MS St. Louis with their twin daughters, Renate and Ines.
Gerd and Rolf Altschul climb on a ladder on the deck of the St. Louis.
An elderly female survivor poses in front of a barred window at the Hadamar Institute, where she was imprisoned for writing anti-Nazi articles.

An envelope of a registered letter sent from  Dabrowa  by Bajla Gertner to Alfred Schwartzbaum in Lausanne, Switzerland.  The return address of the sender or senders states:  Bendsburg, Am Wasser 12/I.  On the back of the envelope there is a piece of tape with a stamp of the German censor.

A document certifying that Mendel Rozenblit has completed the required period of quarantine for typhus at the Dachau concentration camp and may now be released for repatriation.  The release was signed by William A. Smiley, camp surgeon.
Portrait of the donor's son, Heinrich Muller, with a dog in the courtyard behind their home and business in Hlohovec, Czechoslovakia.
Engagement portrait of Leibush Saleschütz and Hannah Gold.
Three religious Jewish men wearing armbands pose on a street in the Bedzin ghetto.
A note written by Dr. Jakob Ferber to the Health department of the Jewish administration of Bedzin requesting the medical assistance of Hanka Granek.
Jozsef Gecse, a Hungarian Nazi who was active in the ghetto, sits next to the body of a Jew killed in the ghetto in Dej
An official letter sent to Melania Elbert stating that she has left the Jewish religion.
The bodies of Jews removed from the Iasi death train during a stop on the journey, are laid out in rows beside the tracks.
A permit given to the Slovak Jew, Alice Elbert, allowing her to travel to a dentist in a nearby town.
Necha Ajzen poses next to her husband's grave in Gorky.

A notice bearing a special stamp that was sent to Marcel Hajsky by the Prague Jewish Council, instructing him how to send a care package to his grandmother, Fanny Goldstein, who was interned in the Theresienstadt concentration camp.  The enclosed stamp had to be attached to any package that was sent to the camp.
A Jewish mother poses with her two daughters at the Fuerth displaced persons camp.
Sketch of five women by Lili Andrieux entitled, "Barracks Interior with Bread and Two Bottles (Version II)."
View of the OSE (Oeuvre de Secours aux Enfants) children's home at Collognes au Mont d'or.
Children in the Hitler Youth and League of German Girls on an outing with their supervisors.
Austrian Jewish refugees pose on the deck of the SS Virgilio on their journey from Italy to Chile.  From Chile they traveled overland to their new homes in La Paz, Bolivia.
Name: Friedrich-Paul von Groszheim
Invitation to the reopening of the Zion clothing and fabric store in Eibergen, which includes a brief account of its history during the war.
Damaged photograph of a group of artist friends in Kovno, Lithuania that survived the destruction of the Kovno ghetto.
Portrait of an unidentified child messenger for the Kovno ghetto Jewish Council, pen and ink drawing by Josef Schlesinger.
A social gathering at the Hitler Jugend Heim (Hitler Youth home) in Poessneck.
Rochel Sutin sits with her daugher, Cecilia, on a park bench in the Neu Freimann displaced persons camp.
Cobblers making boots in the Neu Freimann displaced persons camp.
Pages ten and eleven of the German passport issued to Isidor Abraham (the grandfather of the donor's wife) on April 11, 1939.

The table titled "Emigration from Japan, July 1940-November 1941" from the "Report of the Activity of the Committee for Assistance to Refugees" compiled by the Jewish Community (Jewcom) in Kobe to record the movement of refugees through Japan.
At the liberal Zerrennerstrasse synagogue in Pforzheim, Cantor Hermann Levy blesses Siegbert Levy during his bar mitzvah, while Siegbert's great-uncle (holding the Torah scroll) looks on.
Dr. Michal Eliasberg performs surgery in the Lodz ghetto hospital.
The staff of the Foto-Brenner company at work in their office in Rome.
A woman cries in grief for the loss of her husband and other victims of the Kielce pogrom during the public burial.
A young man on a motorcycle gazes up at a sign posted on a telephone pole that reads, "Jews are not welcomed here."
Group portrait of Jewish refugee children from Germany and London, on the deck of the MS Batory as the ship arrives in Melbourne.
Gisela Soldinger rests on the grass in Bilzen where her family was forced to live in anticipation of deportation back to Germany.
Three young cousins stand on a snowy bridge in Eisiskes.
Ivar Segalowitz rides his tricycle down a street in Memel.
Studio portrait of Dovid Elhanan Moszczenik, a Jewish builder in Eisiskes.
A group of young Zionists pose in front of a shed at a lumberyard in Bedzin prior to the departure of one of their members for Palestine.
Group portrait of Jewish high school students at the Hebrew gymnasium in Mukachevo.
Portrait of Shuduka Benjakar.  She lived at Drinkska 119 in Bitola.
Portrait of Estreya Benjakar, wife of Shabetai Benjakar.  She lived at Kossantschitscheva 7 in Bitola.
Portrait of Isak Eschkenasi.
Portrait of Mois Kamchi, son of Solomon Kamchi.  He was an auto dealer.  He lived at Karagoryeva 107 in Bitola.
Portrait of Isak Koen.  He lived at Novatska 4 in Bitola.
Portrait of Gauleiter Karl Wahl.
Blank Schutzbrief [protective letter] issued by the Portuguese legation to Hungary in 1944.
"World War II Personalities in Cartoons/Originals done for 'La Nacion' Santo Domingo, 1939-1946"
Prewar photo of the Mautner family.
Wedding portrait of Iser Bystryn and Sara Wolksky in 1930.
Portrait of a Jewish father and daughter in Dolina.
Portrait of Field Marshall Wilhelm Ritter von Leeb taken during a recess in the IMT Nuremberg commission hearings investigating indicted Nazi organizations.
David and Paula Schwab pose in front of a car with their two children Gerd and Margot.
View of the courtroom during a session of the International Military Tribunal trial of war criminals at Nuremberg.
Two classmates from the Tarbut school in Luck stand outside a stone porch.

One page of an illustrated album produced by Gyorgy Beifeld (1902-1982), a Hungarian Jew from Budapest, who was drafted into the Munkaszolgalat (Hungarian Labor Service system) and spent more than a year on the Soviet front, from April 1942 through May 1943.  The album contains 402 drawings and watercolors by Byfield, as well as a narrative of his experiences.

Verso of an identification card for Schendel Margosis issued by the Marseilles police stating that she is a Persian citizen and not permitted to work.  The card was stamped by the police at regular intervals.
Isidore Levy poses with his gas mask while serving in the Greek army.
View of the entrance to the Dachau concentration camp with the Prussian eagle perched on top.
Detail of the 14th Street facade of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum.
Pile of discarded personal items and scrap metal in the Pabianice labor camp/storage facility.
A woman holds up two chickens in the open-air market in the Lodz ghetto.
Identification photo from Genia Tola Wasserman's Ausweis which permitted her to work outside the ghetto.
Studio portrait of a Jewish mother and son taken while they were living in hiding in Belgium.
Group portrait of Jewish refugees at the Shanghai airport.
Polish children wearing traditional folk costumes perform folk dances in an orphanage in the Soviet Union run by Marek Liwszyc.
Group portrait of the extended Pisker family.
Meir Katz takes the boys in his cheder class for a boat ride.

One of the two milk cans in which portions of the Ringelblum Oneg Shabbat archives were hidden and buried in the Warsaw ghetto.  The milk cans are currently in the possession of the Jewish Historical Institute in Warsaw.
Group portrait of members of the Kwar family with friends visiting from America.
Studio portrait of a Jewish boy holding a Torah pointer [probably at his Bar Mitzvah].
Two young Jewish brothers wearing matching suits and caps pose next to a hedge in Jaroslaw, Poland.
Children from the Jewish kindergarten (located at 9 Mapu Street) in Kovno, Lithuania, pose outside holding leaves.
Survivors stack corpses outside the crematorium in the newly liberated Buchenwald concentration camp while German civilians look on.
Studio portrait of three Jewish teenage girls in Chechersk, Belarus.
Reichsfuehrer-SS Heinrich Himmler speaks to Karl Wolff (center) in front of a train.
Leaders of the Lampertheim DP camp.
Jacob Zajac, a soldier in the Jewish Brigade, poses with a very young survivor in the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp.
Ernst Jablonsky [Jouhy] works in his office in the Fontenay-aux-Roses children's home.
Five crew members of the President Warfield (later the Exodus 1947), pose around a sign that reads "Baltimore 1946 Special" in Baltimore.
Jewish refugee children gather in a train station in Lisbon prior to their departure for Palestine.
Three passengers relax on deck chairs on board the St. Louis.
Group portrait of German-Jewish children sitting on the steps of the Ons Boschhious children's home in Driebergen.
An American soldier guards the Hungarian Gold Train in Werfen, Austria, soon after the American occupation authorities took custody of the train.
Nazi propaganda poster entitled, "Das bleibt geschrieben," issued by the "Parole der Woche," a wall newspaper (Wandzeitung) published by the National Socialist Party propaganda office in Munich.
Members of Hanoar Hatzioni, a Zionist youth movement, dance with Torah scrolls in celebration of the Jewish holiday, Simchat Torah,  in the Lodz ghetto.
Moisei Kopelman and his son Dmitri rest on a park bench in Kaunas.
Aerial view of a column of German troops marching down Sienna Street shortly after the destruction of the Warsaw ghetto.
Four young children stand in a row next to a toy elephant on the Latvian shore.
Identification card issued to Rosette Bomblat in the Drancy concentration camp where she stayed for two weeks prior to her deporation to Auschwitz.
Studio portrait of a German-Jewish brother and sister praying for their father who was a soldier in World War I.
Members of Maccabi Hatzair meet next to a flag, wearing uniforms.
Mugshot of Nazi defendant Ernst von Weizsaecker, the principal defendant of the Ministries Trial.
Jewish men are forced to shave the beards of other religious Jews while SS men watch in amusement.
Studio portrait of a family of Dutch rescuers and the Jewish child they were hiding.
Two young children sit next to each other on canvas lawn chairs on a grassy field.
Identification card issued to Moniek Szmulewicz testifying that he had been a prisoner in the Buchenwald concentration camp and had been in Nazi prisons since January 1, 1940.
Close-up portrait of a religious Jewish couple.
Three Jewish women in hiding prepare to go to the wedding of their older brother in Nice.
